@ChristianSchwarz 

> Using one event for 2 different cases violates seperation of concerns.

Not necessarily, it might be an _event_ with different state : _success_ or _failure_.

> What I wanted to say is why don't we use 2 SAM interfaces and 2 Event types? This would make the life of event consumer easier, see my comment above.

Yes it's not out of question (my suggestion on the factory methods indeed lean in that direction). But at this moment, I fear we are over-engineering this. @TimvdLippe and @LiamClark are the primary users of this, could you show us some concrete code snippets outside (not tests) how you want the listener to be registered or how the code you're working with can/should process the _verifications_.

Basically the design question is wether we want this :

``` java
Mockito.framework().addListener((VerificationFailure) System.out::println);
Mockito.framework().addListener((VerificationSuccess) System.out::println);

interface Verification { verificationMode, wantedMethod, verificationData }
interface VerificationFailure extends Verification { failureCause }
interface VerificationFailureListener extends MockitoListener {
        void on(VerificationFailure arg);
}
interface VerificationSuccess extends Verification { }
interface VerificationSuccessListener extends MockitoListener {
        void on(VerificationSuccess arg);
}
```

Or 

``` java
Mockito.framework().addListener((Verification) System.out::println);

// could be with sub-interfaces or public classes VerificationFailure and VerificationSuccess
interface Verification { verificationMode, wantedMethod, verificationData, failureCause }
interface VerificationListener extends MockitoListener {
        void on(Verification arg);
}
```
